Context: Limberlost Place is a 10-storey net-zero carbon emissions building scheduled to open in the summer of 2024 at George Brown College. It will be made of nationally sourced mass timber components and set new standards for green building. The site is located directly north of the Daphne Cockwell Centre for Health Sciences, and guests were given a sneak peek of the foundation, mechanical and electrical system rough-ins, forming of columns, tunnel entrance to the Daphne Cockwell Centre for Health Sciences, pedestrian bridge joining the two buildings, future childcare centre, and fitness centre. Chancellor Emeritus Sally Horsfall Eaton and business leader and philanthropist Jack Cockwell attended tours and groundbreaking ceremony of Limberlost Place. Cockwell donated $18 million to the project, which is the largest donation to an Ontario college. The building will be the first institutional building of its kind in Ontario. To learn more about Limberlost Place and supporting students' success through George Brown College Foundation or application deadlines, college news, upcoming events, visit their website. The text also mentions a land acknowledgment but no further details are provided.
